Customer use case:
{quote}
We use SVN as our repository. We use a fairly traditional trunk and branch structure. Our current review process requires us to create a "review" branch for each review. One reason for this is to be able to do trunk pre-commit reviews. I know that crucible has a pre-commit review capability, but frankly, it will not do what we want. So, we use a "svn cp" command to create a branch and copy our changed files in 1 step to a review branch (this creates a single checkin from the copy and commit of the new files). Doing traditional SVN diffs, it is smart enough to realize that the branch has a base and does not include any of the copied files as part of the diff, only the changed files. We also do the same process for creating a review branch from a traditional private working branch.

Anyhow, when I try to use crucible with our review branch, it is trying to pull in way to many files (maybe all of them). First, is this expected? Second, if not, how do I setup Crucible to correctly determine branch bases. I have setup my own set of SVN Symbolic Rules to match our structure. Please let me know if any additional details are required. Thank you for your quick response.
{quote}

This might be a common use case - where users branch and want to add all new commits on the branchX to a review.

{quote}
We have a commit with a +review in the commit message. It triggers a review as expected. But all files in that commit are excluded files for that repo. I don't see a way to make Crucible skip review creation for such cases in the Crucible settings. We want to avoid additional scripting and duplicating the same excludes in the Git hooks to filter out such cases.
{quote}

{quote}
Second - is there a way to set the defaults for the issue create dialog? 
{quote}

In the [Managing Add-Ons page|https://confluence.atlassian.com/display/CRUCIBLE/Managing+add-ons] the following can be read:
{quote}
An add-on is an installable component that supplements or enhances the functionality of Crucible in some way. For example, the Automatic Review Creator automatically creates a Crucible review each time a commit is made to a FishEye repository.
{quote}

Yet, the [Automatic Review Creator|https://marketplace.atlassian.com/plugins/com.atlassian.example.reviewcreator] is supported only up to FishEye/Crucible 2.3.7. Perhaps this reference should be removed in order to avoid confusion.

This is valid for FishEye/Crucible [2.9.0|https://confluence.atlassian.com/display/CRUCIBLE029/Managing+add-ons] as well.

In the [Crucible and FishEye page], under "Setting up a repository for use with stand-alone Crucible" the following can be read:
{quote}
When accessing repositories from stand-alone Crucible, the SCM client interface will access the repositories on demand. This requires that you configure the plugin.
{quote}
Unless this is still referring to the [lightSCM plugins|https://confluence.atlassian.com/display/CRUCIBLE/Advantages+of+Native+Repository+Access+over+lightSCM+plugins], Crucible does not access the repositories on demand nor does it need to configure the plugin.

The same is valid for [2.8.0|https://confluence.atlassian.com/display/CRUCIBLE028/Crucible+and+FishEye] and [2.9.0|https://confluence.atlassian.com/display/CRUCIBLE029/Crucible+and+FishEye].
